newsitem.title: USA: US late prods fall as NYMEX changes direction.
newsitem.headline: US late prods fall as NYMEX changes direction.

text.p: U.S. spot products fell moderately by late Friday as NYMEX futures pulled back from Thursday gains and New York gasoline differentials continued to ease amid stronger imports, players said.
New York Harbor conventional unleaded M2-grade gasoline fell about 0.85 cent a gallon, with bids about 3.00 cents below September futures --about 0.30 cent weaker than Thursday diffs, players said.
And diffs slipped about 0.20 cent on NYH reformulated A2-grade material, traders said, with bids at about 0.40 cent above the print.
Players said at least 13 cargoes from Europe and South America were expected to begin reaching East Coast markets starting Friday, exerting downward pressure on diffs.
"Most of the cargoes are already placed with majors, which means they won't be buying as much," one East Coast trader said, speculating prices could continue softening in the next week.
Heating oil fell about a half cent tracking futures in both centers, players said, with differentials holding steady.
On Thursday, higher NYMEX values had lifted distillates 1.50 cents a gallon and pushed New York Harbor conventional unleaded gasoline 0.60 cent higher despite weaker diffs.

"Nobody can figure out how the Merc (NYMEX) is making up its mind," one frustrated East Coast trader said, noting that NYMEX prices this week have alternated day-to-day between strongly higher and sharply lower values.
-- Ransdell Pierson, New York Energy Desk 212 859-1632
